answers.body_markdown:
You need to break down into different parts and use Random from `Java.util.Random`
Then loop to generate the numbers and append - at the end, checking if we are at last part to not add it. Also it can be done by making a substring to last character after the loop.



    private static final Random RANDOM = new Random();
      public static String randomStringId() {
        StringBuilder id = new StringBuilder();

        int[] parts = {8, 4, 4, 4, 12};
         for (int i = 0; i &lt; parts.length; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j &lt; parts[i]; j++) {
                id.append(RANDOM.nextInt(9) + 1);
            }
            if (i!=parts.length-1) {
                id.append(&quot;-&quot;);
            }
        }
        return id.toString();
    }

An alternative wthout changing a lot of what you already have, could be to use a `MaskFormatter`:

    //import java.text.ParseException;
    //import javax.swing.text.MaskFormatter;

    public static String randomStringId() throws ParseException {
        MaskFormatter mask = new MaskFormatter(&quot;########-####-####-####-############&quot;);
        mask.setValueContainsLiteralCharacters(false);

        String numberList = &quot;0123456789&quot;;
        StringBuilder numberValue = new StringBuilder();

        for (int i = 0; i &lt; 32; i++) {
            numberValue.append(numberList.charAt(new Random().nextInt(numberList.length())));
        }

        return mask.valueToString(numberValue.toString());
    }

Feel like a code-golf challenge :) Following is a garbage-free variant.

```java
    private static final Random RANDOM = new Random();
    private static final StringBuilder PATTERN = new StringBuilder(&quot;xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx&quot;);
    public static synchronized String randomStringId() {
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; PATTERN.length(); i++) {
            if (PATTERN.charAt(i) != &#39;-&#39;) PATTERN.setCharAt(i, (char) (48 + RANDOM.nextInt(10)));
        }
        return PATTERN.toString();
    }
```

FYI 48 is ASCII for character &#39;0&#39;. So `48 + random(10)` gives you random chars between &#39;0&#39; and &#39;9&#39;.

