To configure Spring Security **In-Memory Authentication**,
add **UserDetailsService** bean in your **SecurityConfiguration** class, with User Name and Password for authentication.

Example:

    @Configuration
    public class SecurityConfiguration
    {
	    @Bean
        public UserDetailsService userDetailsService() 
	    {
            //User Role
            UserDetails theUser = User.withUsername(&quot;sergey&quot;)
                                      .passwordEncoder(PasswordEncoderFactories.createDelegatingPasswordEncoder()::encode)
                                      .password(&quot;12345678&quot;).roles(&quot;USER&quot;).build();
        
            //Manager Role 
            UserDetails theManager = User.withUsername(&quot;john&quot;)
                                         .passwordEncoder(PasswordEncoderFactories.createDelegatingPasswordEncoder()::encode)
                                        .password(&quot;12345&quot;).roles(&quot;MANAGER&quot;).build();
        
  
           InMemoryUserDetailsManager userDetailsManager = new InMemoryUserDetailsManager();
              
           userDetailsManager.createUser(theUser);
           userDetailsManager.createUser(theManager);
        
           return userDetailsManager;
       }
    }

**Reference Document:** https://www.appsdeveloperblog.com/spring-security-in-memory-authentication/

